paragraphs.title: Bike demand prediction for stations in NYC
paragraphs.text:
%md

This notebook provides a sample set of R code, leveraging the Zeppelin %r interpreter and the OML4Spark capabilities to interact with data from different sources to determine an appropriate linear regression model to predict the availability of bikes at specific stations throughout the course of a day. 

There are 6 sections to this Sample which should all be run in order:

    1. Initiate the OML4Spark environment - Load the libraries and create an exclusive Spark Session on the Cluster
    2. Load the dataset from CSV file or HDFS -  shows how to read a file from the file system or HDFS and load it as a Spark DataFrame
    3. Process the data using Spark SQL to create new attributes and to split the data into Training and Test
    4. Determine Appropriate Model running R code to execute several linear regression model using OML4Spark Spark-based LM
    5. Run a prediction on the Test Dataset, and diagnose model quality using Actuals vs. Predicted
    6. List Bike Demand per Station ID at different days of the week

paragraphs.title: _____________________   2 - Load the dataset from CSV file on HDFS   _____________________
Loads the historical Bike Demand data directly from a CSV on Hadoop HDFS into a Spark DF

paragraphs.title: __________   3 - Use SparkSQL to create new attributes and split into Training/Test   __________
Use Spark SQL inside OML4Spark to directly transform columns in a view of the Spark Dataframe
paragraphs.text:
%r
# Create a SQL View so we can use SQL to create numerical columns with Seconds from the "time" columns 
orch.df.createView(station, viewName = 'tempView')

# Run the Spark SQL query creating several new columns
station_status <- orch.df.sql(paste0('select num_docks_available, station_id, weekday_num, num_bikes_disabled,',
                                     'num_docks_disabled,prev_docks_available, dock_diff, trips_ended,', 
                                     'substr(last_reported_time, 1,2)*3600+',
                                     'substr(last_reported_time, 4,2)*60 as last_reported_time,',
                                     'substr(interval_start, 1,2)*3600+',
                                     'substr(interval_start, 4,2)*60 as interval_start ',
                                     'from tempView'))
                     
# Visualize the resulting Spark DataFrame
zshow(station_status)

# Optionally show the types of columns in the Spark DataFrame
# station_status$printSchema()

paragraphs.title: Using Spark's randomSplitAsList function, split the Spark DataFrame into Training (60%) and Test (40%) and show counts
paragraphs.text:
%r
# Split the Spark Dataframe into Training and Test, using 60% for training and 40% for test
splits <- .jarray(c(0.6,0.4))
seed <- .jlong(1234L)
# Split Randomly as a list of 2 Spark DataFrames using the proportion for Training requested
splitStations <- station_status$randomSplitAsList( splits , seed)

# Assign the training name to the first (60%) Split, and Count it
training <- splitStations$get(0L)

# Assign the test name to the second (40%) Split, and Count it
test <- splitStations$get(1L)
print(paste0('Training Count: ',training$count(),' rows | Test Count: ',test$count(),' rows'))

paragraphs.title: __________   4 - Build several Regression models in Spark via OML4Spark LM and evaluate model quality    __________
Build 7 different Regression Models, varying the input columns
paragraphs.text:
%r
# Prepare a list to receive all Model Resutls
model_dock_demand <- list()
# Build several linear regression model to predict dock_demand recursing the number of variables to find the best model
model_dock_demand[[1]] <- orch.lm2(formula = num_docks_available ~ as.factor(station_id) + as.factor(weekday_num) + num_bikes_disabled + num_docks_disabled+
                                   dock_diff + trips_ended + last_reported_time + interval_start,
                                   data = training, verbose=FALSE)

#remove last_reported_time
model_dock_demand[[2]] <- orch.lm2(formula = num_docks_available ~ as.factor(station_id) + as.factor(weekday_num) + num_bikes_disabled + num_docks_disabled +
                                   dock_diff + trips_ended + interval_start,
                                   data = training, verbose=FALSE)

#remove prev_docks_available
model_dock_demand[[3]] <- orch.lm2(formula = num_docks_available ~ as.factor(station_id) + as.factor(weekday_num) + num_bikes_disabled + num_docks_disabled +
                                   dock_diff + trips_ended + interval_start,
                                   data = training, verbose=FALSE)
#remove num_bikes_disabled
model_dock_demand[[4]] <- orch.lm2(formula = num_docks_available ~ as.factor(station_id) + as.factor(weekday_num) + num_docks_disabled + dock_diff + trips_ended + 
                                   interval_start,
                                   data = training, verbose=FALSE)

#remove dock_diff
model_dock_demand[[5]] <- orch.lm2(formula = num_docks_available ~ as.factor(station_id) + as.factor(weekday_num) + num_docks_disabled + trips_ended + interval_start,
                                   data = training, verbose=FALSE)

#remove num_docks_disabled
model_dock_demand[[6]] <- orch.lm2(formula = num_docks_available ~ as.factor(station_id) + as.factor(weekday_num) + trips_ended + interval_start,
                                   data = training, verbose=FALSE)

#remove trips_ended
model_dock_demand[[7]] <- orch.lm2(formula = num_docks_available ~ as.factor(station_id) + as.factor(weekday_num) + interval_start,
                                   data = training, verbose=FALSE)

paragraphs.title: Extract Model Statistics for comparison
paragraphs.text:
%r
# Extract the Model statistics R Squares, RSS and Number of Coefficients for comparison
model_stats <- function(dat) {cbind(dat$summary$r.squared,
                                    dat$summary$rss,
                                    length(dat$summary$coefficients)-1)}

# Apply function for extracting the Stats from Models
model_results <- lapply(model_dock_demand, model_stats)

# "Flatten" the output into a Data Frame so it is more readable
final_stats <- as.data.frame(do.call(rbind, model_results) )

model_num <- 1:nrow(final_stats)

final_out <- cbind(model_num, final_stats)

names(final_out) <- c('Model_number','R_Squared','RSS','Num_Coefficients')

# List of Models to identify the best model fit quality
zshow(final_out)

paragraphs.title: _____________________   5 - Run a prediction on test data and assess one of the models    _____________________
Assessing model quality visually: Actuals (X axis) vs. Predicted (Y axis)
paragraphs.text:
%r
# For prediction, we can load the test dataset

# Create a SQL View so we can select only the needed columns for the Model
orch.df.createView(test, viewName = 'tempView_test')
station_test <- orch.df.sql(paste0('select num_docks_available, station_id, weekday_num, num_bikes_disabled, 
                                    num_docks_disabled, dock_diff, trips_ended, interval_start ',
                                    'from tempView_test'))

# Predict the entire test set of around 487k rows
station_predictions <- predict(model_dock_demand[[3]], station_test, 
                               supplemental = c("num_docks_available","station_id", "weekday_num", 
                                                "trips_ended","interval_start") )

# Show the prediction Spark DF output
zshow(station_predictions)
